Matrix as a Linear Transformation¶

Applied Machine Learning¶

By Audrey Nguyen¶

Matrix A is an object that "acts" (or "operates") on a vector x by multiplication to produce a new vector called Ax. The original vector is x, and the transformed vector is Ax. An ensemble of vectors are transformed using several different matrices (i.e. several different transformations).

Simple dataset of points are plotted, where each point represents an individual vector in 2D Cartesian space. Several different geometric linear transformations are performed in real 2D space on this data. The transformation can be view by the plotting of both the original data and the transformed data.

Functions for Plotting the Transformation¶

A function called plotTransformedData(original_df, trans_df, colors, size, limits) was created that accepts two Pandas DataFrames (composed of 2 spatial coordinates each) called original_df and trans_df. Additionally, the plotTransformedData function accepts three other parameters: colors, size, and limits.

  • The colors parameter is passed to the scatter function through its c parameter. The colors parameter is a (n,3) NumPy array, where n is the number of data points and each of the three columns corresponds to an RGB value in the range [0,1]. The first point is black and the last point is red.
  • The size parameter is passed to the scatter function through its s parameter. The size parameter controls the size of the marker used to represent the data point, and is a Numpy array of size (n,). (The np.linspace() was used to create the array).
  • Finally, the limits parameter is a list that looks like this: limits = [xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax], where the values are the limits for the x and y axes. These limits values were set to -2.25 and +2.25 for both x and y as limits).
In [20]:
#=================================================================================================================
# DEFINE FUNCTION FOR TRANSFORMING A MATRIX IN A MATRIX MULTIPLICATION AND PLOTTING IT NEXT TO THE ORIGINAL MATRIX                                   
#=================================================================================================================

#Transforms original matrix in matrix multiplication. Plots the original and transformed matrix
def transformMatrixInMatrixMultiplication(original_matrix, transformation_matrix):
    
    import numpy as np
    

    #===================================================================
    # TRANSFORM A MATRIX BY LINEAR TRANSFORMATION OF THE ORIGINAL MATRIX                         
    #===================================================================
    #Matrix multiplication of the original matrix and the transformation matrix, both as Numpy array.
    #This is a linear transformation of the original matrix resulting in it to be transformed matrix 
    A_transformed = np.dot(original_matrix,transformation_matrix)

    #Convert Numpy array to DataFrame
    original_matrix = pd.DataFrame(original_matrix, columns = ['x', 'y'])
    A_transformed = pd.DataFrame(A_transformed, columns = ['x', 'y'])


    #===============================================================================
    # PLOT ORIGINAL AND TRANSFORMED MATRICES TO VIEW BEFORE AND AFTER TRANSFORMATION                         
    #===============================================================================

    #IMPORTS
    from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

    #SET DIFFERENT COLOR FOR EACH DATAPOINTS 
    #Colors from black to different shades of red (darker intensity to lighter intensity of red)
    #Each of the three columns corresponds to an RGB value in the range [0,1].
    #Each row represents a datapoint
    colors =  np.linspace(start=[0, 0, 0], stop=[1, 0, 0], num=25)

    #SET SIZE OF EACH DATAPOINT
    #size parameter controls the size of the marker used to represent the data point, and is a Numpy array of size (𝑛,) 
    size = np.linspace(15,90,25)

    #SET LIMITS OF THE X AND Y AXES
    #limits parameter is a list that looks like: limits=[xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax], where the values are the limits for the x and y axes. 
    xmin=-2.25
    xmax=2.25
    ymin=-2.25
    ymax=2.25 
    limits=[xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax]

    
    #PLOT ORIGINAL AND TRANSFORMED MATRICES WITH SPECIFIED COLORS, SIZES, AND LIMITS
    plotTransformedData(original_matrix, A_transformed, colors, size, limits)
In [3]:
#================================================================
# DEFINE FUNCTION FOR PLOTTING BOTH ORIGINAL AND TRANSFORMED DATA                                       
#================================================================

#PLOT BOTH ORIGINAL AND TRANSFORMED DATA. PASSED 2 DATAFRAMES COMPOSED OF 2 SPATIAL COORDINATES EACH
def plotTransformedData(original_df, trans_df, colors, size, limits):
  
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    from mpl_toolkits import mplot3d
    import numpy as np
     
    #SIZE OF A PLOT
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = [16, 4])  
    
    #=============================
    #PLOT ORIGINAL DATA DATAFRAME:
    #=============================
    #ADD SUBPLOT IN ROW 1 AND COLUMN 1 INSIDE A PLOT WITH 1 ROW AND 2 COLUMNS
    fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)     
    
    #GET ARRAY OF X COORDINATES AND AN ARRAY OF Y COORDINATES FROM ORIGINAL DATA DATAFRAME
    #TO PASS THEM TO plt.scatter() METHOD
    x_original = original_df['x']
    y_original = original_df['y']
    
    #FUNCTION FOR PLOTTING DATA. 
    plt.scatter(x_original, y_original, c=colors, s=size)
    
    #The xlim() and ylim() functions is used to get or set the x-limits and y-limits of the current axes.
    plt.xlim(limits[0],limits[1])     # first parameter: minimum number, second parameter: maximum number on x-axis
    plt.ylim(limits[2],limits[3])     # first parameter: minimum number, second parameter: maximum number on y-axis

    #Label title of the plot
    plt.title("Original Data", fontsize=16)
    #Label y-axis
    plt.ylabel("$y$", fontsize=16, rotation=0)
    #Label x-axis
    plt.xlabel("$x$", fontsize=16)


    #================================
    #PLOT TRANSFORMED DATA DATAFRAME:
    #================================
    #SUBPLOT IN ROW 1 AND COLUMN 2 INSIDE A PLOT WITH 1 ROW AND 2 COLUMNS
    fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)     

    #GET ARRAY OF X COORDINATES AND AN ARRAY OF Y COORDINATES FROM TRANSFORMED DATA DATAFRAME
    #TO PASS THEM TO plt.scatter() METHOD
    x_transformed = trans_df['x']
    y_transformed = trans_df['y']
    
    #FUNCTION FOR PLOTTING DATA. 
    plt.scatter(x_transformed, y_transformed, c=colors, s=size)

    #The xlim() and ylim() functions is used to get or set the x-limits and y-limits of the current axes.
    plt.xlim(limits[0],limits[1])     # first parameter: minimum number, second parameter: maximum number on x-axis
    plt.ylim(limits[2],limits[3])     # first parameter: minimum number, second parameter: maximum number on y-axis

    #Label title of the plot
    plt.title("Transformed Data", fontsize=16)
    #Label y-axis
    plt.ylabel("$y$", fontsize=16, rotation=0)
    #Label x-axis
    plt.xlabel("$x$", fontsize=16)

    #=========
    #SHOW PLOT
    #=========
    plt.show()

Define Data Matrix and Transformation Matrices¶

The following transformation matrices were defined:

In [6]:
#=====================================
# DEFINE DATA MATRIX (ORIGINAL MATRIX)
#=====================================
#Create numpy array X from data dataframe. This is the original matrix
X = np.array(data)

#==================================
# DEFINE 13 TRANSFORMATION MATRICES
#==================================
#Create numpy array of each of the transformation matrices
#AN = np.array[[x1,y1],[x2,y2]]
A1 = np.array([[-1,0],[0,-1]])
A2 = np.array([[0.5,0],[0,1]])
A3 = np.array([
               [round(math.cos(math.pi/4)), round(math.sin(math.pi/4))], 
               [round(-(math.sin(math.pi/4))), round(math.cos(math.pi/4))]
            ])
A4 = np.array([[-1,0],[0,1]])
A5 = np.array([[1,0],[0,2.0]])
A6 = np.array([[1,0.5],[0,1]])
A7 = np.array([[1,0],[0.5,1]])
A8 = np.array([[0,-1],[-1,0]])
A9 = np.array([[1,0],[0,0]])
A10 = np.array([[0,0],[0,1]])
A11 = np.array([[1,0],[0,-1]])
A12 = np.array([[0,1],[1,0]])
A13 = np.array([[1,0],[0,1]])

Perform Linear Transformations and Plot Results¶

X_transformed = A x X_transposed

Where X_transformed is the data that was read in from the file, A is any one of the thirteen transformation matrices, and X_transformed is the transformed data.

Identity Matrix on Original Matrix:¶

Any matrix A multiplied by the Identity Matrix I is equal to itself! That is, AI=A. The 2D identity matrix is given below.

In [7]:
#===============================================
# MATRIX MULTIPLICATION WITH IDENTITY MATRIX 'I'
#===============================================
#Convert data dataframe to numpy array and name it matrix A
A = np.array(data)

#===============
#IDENTITY MATRIX
#===============
#Assigned I to A13. A13 same as an Identity Matrix.
I = A13    

#====================================================================================================
#TRANSFORMATION OF ORIGINAL MATRIX USING IDENTITY MATRIX AND PLOTTING ORIGINAL AND TRANSFORMED MATRIX
#====================================================================================================
#Transform original matrix using identity matrix  
#using transformMatrixInMatrixMultiplication(original_matrix_np_array, transformation_matrix_np_array) method 
#which uses plotTransformedData(original_matrix_df, transformed_matrix_df, colors, size, limits) method in it
transformMatrixInMatrixMultiplication(A,I)
